\begin_layout Title
Polarimeter concepts for the EDM precursor experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{P. Maanen{}^{a}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{J. Pretz}^{a,b}$
\end_inset

 for the JEDI Collaboration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed method for a search for an Electric Dipole Moment of charged
 particles consists of storing the particles in a storage ring and letting
 the charged particles interact with a radial electric field.
 Starting with a horizontally polarized beam, the EDM signal would be a
 vertical polarization build-up.
 If the EDMs of deuteron and proton are in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-29}\textrm{e\cdot cm}$
\end_inset

, the polarization build-up due to the EDM is in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{nrad/s}$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming a horizontal polarization lifetime of 
\begin_inset Formula $1000\,\textrm{s}$
\end_inset

, this means the vertical polarization to be detected is in the order of
 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

For the polarization measurement, nuclear scattering which uses spin-dependent
 asymmetries in the nuclear scattering cross section to measure the beam
 polarization was chosen.
 A vertical polarization is associated with a left-right asymmetry in the
 scattering cross section while a longitudinal polarization leads to a up-down
 asymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Polarimeter design goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To achieve the necessary precision, the EDM polarimeter should achieve the
 following goals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Large statistical figure of merit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Minimal influence on the beam 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
High sensitivity to systematic effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Good long term stability and reproducibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Simple concept
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The statistical figure of merit of a polarimeter is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\sigma\cdot A_{y}^{2}$
\end_inset

 which means to maximize the statistical accuracy of a polarimeter one has
 to simply choose the process with the highest possible cross section and
 analyzing power.
 The influence on the beam should be minimal to none because even the slightest
 pertubation can influence the beam on a noticeable level.
 In the past it has been demonstrated that it is possible to control the
 systematic uncertainties to the 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}$
\end_inset

 level by calibration of the detector by inducing large errors in the beam
 and measuring the variation of the output 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brantjes201249"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

