\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Target type
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, many different target types are available for use.
 Solid State Targets in general are easier to handle than cluster and gas
 targets and target densities in the order of magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{20}\,\textrm{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 are easily achievable.
 Cluster targets can achieve target densities of up to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}\,\mathrm{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 - 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{15}\,\mathrm{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

.
 The target currently used for R&D measurements is a carbon slab with several
 cm in thickness.
 For extraction the beam is placed close to the target and then heated by
 application of white noise 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysRevLett.115.094801"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, a research has begun to develop a new type of target that uses
 small diamond pellets to continuosly extract the beam without needing external
 electrical fields 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jedi"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

